vec_images=np.asarray([np.reshape(img,(img.shape[0]*img.shape[1])) for img in centered_images])
#print(vec_images.shape)

m=vec_images.shape[0]
d=vec_images.shape[1]

# m is total no of images
#d is the dimension of flatenned image
print('no of images : :', m)
cov_matrix=np.zeros(d*d)
cov_matrix=np.reshape(cov_matrix,(d,d))
for i in range(m):
    cov_matrix+=(np.outer(vec_images[i],vec_images[i]))
#cov_matrix=np.outer(vec_images[0],vec_images[0])
cov_matrix=cov_matrix/m

Eigen Values and Eigen Faeces¶

  • Next we will find eigen vales and eigen faces
  • Sort eigen vales in descending order
  • first k eigenvectors corresponding to the first eigen
    values will be taken as eigen faces

Getting Coefficients¶

Now we try to get the coefficients for a given image corresponding
corresponding to different eigen faces

In [45]:
#img passed to this function has to be 
# a flatenned image 
# 1D numpy array
def get_img_cf(img, eig_faces,mean_img):
    img=img-mean_img
    c_img=[]
    no_of_eig_faces=eig_faces.shape[0]
    #eig_faces=eig_vec[0:no_of_eig_faces,:]
    #print(eig_faces.shape)
    for i in range(no_of_eig_faces):
        c_img.append(np.dot(img,eig_faces[i]))
    c_img=np.asarray(c_img)
    return(c_img)
#print(c_img)

Follow, we try to regenerate the image from the given eigen faces

In [46]:
def reconstruct_img(c_img,eig_faces):
    recon_img=np.zeros(eig_faces.shape[1])
    for i in range(eig_faces.shape[0]):
        recon_img+=c_img[i]*eig_faces[i]
    recon_img=recon_img+mean_img.reshape(1,64*64)    
    return(recon_img)

Calculating residuals¶

Now with given number of eigenfaces we are able to reconstruct the
given image, so here we wil test how good our algorihm is working to
project dxd dimensional image to a lower imensional space
we will now subtract the given imaeges and then compare the difference
we will plot the difference image also
Jst for some fun

In [47]:
def calc_residual(img1,img2):
    res_pic=(img1-img2)
    res=np.sum(img1-img2)
    return(res,res_pic)
In [77]:
def test_PCA(img,no_EF,plot=False):
    eig_fc=eig_vec[0:no_EF,:]
    mean=np.reshape(mean_img,(1,64*64))
    coeff=get_img_cf(img,eig_fc,mean)
    r_img=reconstruct_img(coeff,eig_fc)
    res,res_pic=calc_residual(r_img,img)
    
    if(plot):
        fig=plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
        ax1=fig.add_subplot(1,3,1,xticks=[],yticks=[])
        ax1.imshow(r_img.reshape(64,64), cmap='gray')
        ax1.set_title('original image')

        ax2=fig.add_subplot(1,3,2,xticks=[],yticks=[])
        ax2.imshow(img.reshape(64,64), cmap='gray')
        ax2.set_title('reconstructed image')

        ax3=fig.add_subplot(1,3,3,xticks=[],yticks=[])
        ax3.imshow(res_pic.reshape(64,64), cmap='gray')
        ax3.set_title('residual image')
        plt.show()
        
        print('scalar Residual value :: ',res)
        
        return(res,fig)
    else:
        return(res)

Inference¶

  • The PCA is able to reconstruct train image effectively
    with 1000 eigen-faces, the residual is extremely small
    of the order of 10e(-7)
  • It is able to reconstruct test_faces also
    which were not involved in calculation of eigen faces
    residual is of the order of 0.1
  • On external image containing face also, we are able to reconstruct image with
    residual of the order of 700
    this rather high residual is de to the fact that the external image is not pre-processed yet.
  • The proof of concept that we are able to reconstruct the image is that
    with an external non-face image the residual is much higher
  • At this point, with fixing p certain threshold , we cam classify given image as "face-image" or "non-face image"
